# Testing

## What a change owes the test suite

Any behavioral change ships with tests unless the project has none (then note it). The floor per changed behavior:
- the happy path
- one boundary (empty input, zero, max, exactly-at-limit)
- one failure path (invalid input, dependency error) asserting the ERROR behavior, not just "it throws"

Bug fixes get a regression test that fails on the old code — write it first when practical; watching it fail proves it tests the right thing.

## Test quality — the difference between a suite and a liability

- **Test behavior through public interfaces**, not implementation details. A refactor that preserves behavior should not break tests.

```ts
// ❌ Implementation-coupled — breaks on refactor      // ✅ Behavior
expect(cartService._recalculate).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(2);
expect(cart.items.length).toBe(2);                      expect(getTotal(cart)).toBe(3980);
                                                        expect(applyCoupon(cart, "X10").total).toBe(3582);
```

- Names state the behavior: `rejects_expired_coupon_with_COUPON_EXPIRED`, not `test_coupon_2`.
- One behavior per test. Arrange–Act–Assert visible. Shared setup via fixtures/factories, not 40 lines of copy-paste per test.
- **Determinism is absolute**: fake the clock, seed randomness, stub network at the boundary, isolate all shared state. A test that passes 95% of the time is worth less than no test — it trains everyone to ignore red.
- Mock at system boundaries (HTTP, DB if the project does, time, fs) — not your own internal functions; over-mocking tests the mocks.
- Assert specifically: `expect(result.status).toBe("shipped")` beats `expect(result).toBeTruthy()`. Snapshot tests only for genuinely stable serialized output, reviewed like code.

## Forbidden moves (these are integrity violations, not shortcuts)

- Deleting/skipping a failing test to go green.
- Loosening an assertion until it passes (`toBe(42)` → `toBeDefined()`).
- Hardcoding the function to return the expected test value.
- Increasing timeouts to mask a race instead of fixing the race.
- If you believe a failing test is WRONG: make the case explicitly to the user (what it asserts, why that's outdated, what correct looks like) — then change it with consent.

## Running & reporting

- Narrowest scope first (single file) for the loop; widest affordable scope before declaring done.
- READ the summary: "0 tests collected" or "3 skipped" exiting 0 is NOT a pass. Confirm your new tests actually ran.
- Report the literal command and literal result: `pnpm vitest run src/cart — 14 passed (3 new)`. Never round "mostly passing" up to "passing."
- A test failing only in CI/another env is still failing. Investigate env deltas (tz, locale, parallelism, versions); don't shrug it off as flake without evidence.
